name: 3-chloro-2-fluorobenzamide
Reason: The base structure for 3-chloro-2-fluorobenzamide is benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5 °C. Each substituent on the benzene ring will modify this base melting point. The amide group (-CONH2) is known to significantly increase the melting point due to its ability to form strong hydrogen bonds, as well as introduce dipole moments and possible intermolecular interactions such as amide-amide hydrogen bonding; this can be estimated as a +80°C increase. The chlorine atom is relatively heavy and also electronegative, leading to stronger van der Waals forces and dipoles; it could contribute approximately +40°C. The fluorine atom, being highly electronegative, will contribute to strong dipole-dipole interactions and an increase in the melting point; this may be a further +30°C. Combining these effects, you would estimate an increase of 150°C from the base melting point of benzene.
